{"key":"processedPost-9857991","value":{"id":9857991,"first":9857522,"last":9858231,"when":1235524122,"utime":"02/25/09 03:08 AM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /> How do you know when your LC is dead?<br /></blockquote><br /><br />You don't.&nbsp; This is why I recommend against making LC from spores.&nbsp; You never know if it's healthy or contaminated until you use it, thus all that time it's spent growing slower than any other medium is wasted.&nbsp; If you transfer contaminated or weak mycelium from one LC to another, you simply spread the problem.<br /><br />If you want to expand mycelium fast, learn to proof your cultures on agar, and then take them to sterilized grains.&nbsp; It will be much faster and you'll always know what you have.&nbsp; If you need LC at that point, you can always add sterilized water to the jar of colonized grains, shake it up, and then draw the water back out.&nbsp; This will give you myceliated water at least 100 times faster than growing from spores in a sugar or honey water mix.<br />RR","title":"Re: How do you know when your LC is dead?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}